@node Introduction
@prev Main

Welcome to HAL 9001, Also known as Nicolas.
The name HAL comes from a well known science fiction movie/book. The name
Nicolas is an acronym that I thought up in a particularly imaginative
moment. It stands for Non-Inteligent COmputer LAnguage System. Clever, eh?
The program will be referred to as HAL from now on, because it's easier
to type.

This program is designed basically as a fun little toy for you to experiment
with. It isn't likely to ever have any real purpose other than that. The
program is an Artificial Inteligence experiment. It's claim to fame is that
it can create sentences that are understandable and have meaning. Truth,
accuracy and context it may not know, but at least the sentences will be,
shall we say, grammatically correct.

The program comes with a very small dictionary built into it, in case it is
unable to find it's disk based dictionary. This built in dictionary is
somewhat small, however, and although it'll take a long time to ever repeat
a sentence even from that small selection, they will all start sounding very
similar very quickly unless you enlarge it's dictionary by entering some
sentences of your own.

            @{"Back to begining" link Main}
@endnode

@node Overview

Using the HAL 9001:
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
There are two ways you can use HAL 9001: First, you could just load it and
press enter repeatedly. The computer will produce a string of randomly
created sentences from it's existing dictionary. These will give you some
idea of the sort of sentences the program outputs. Next, you could try
inputting your own sentences instead of just pressing return. Try to enter
sentences in the same basic format as those the computer produces: The
computer should be able to handle most other sentence constructions, but may
not be able to link the words correctly which may result in some strange
sentences being thrown back at you!

If you enter any words that the computer does not know about, or is unsure
of, it will ask you some questions so that it can put it into it's
dictionary in the correct place. The questions go along the lines of "What
type of word is XYZ?", "Is it singular or plural?". All these questions
require just one key to be pressed, usually the first letter of the answer
(eg press N if your word is a noun, etc).

The computer tries to be quite intelligent when asking questions. If a noun
is preceded with the word "a" or "an", for example, it won't bother asking
if it is singular or plural.

As you enter more and more data, you will find the sentences the computer
produces become more and more varied.


Note: The 'questions' feature is new and experimental. Although the computer
makes good sentences when asking questions, I have not yet adjusted the
parser to cope with sentences like this being input.
The parser is designed to try to interpret whatever you throw at it, but I'm
not making any guarantees that it will work correctly given a question.
Statement-style sentences, like those the program has always used, continue
to work fine.


            @{"Show me a sample" link Sample}

            @{"Back to begining" link main}

@endnode

@node Sample "Some sample output."

Some samples
~~~~~~~~~~~~

So... You're still completely baffled. What @{i}is@{ui} this program supposed
to do?

Well, I suggest your best bet is just to try it out. Go on - it's good fun.

But to whet your appetite a bit, this page shows basically what the computer
can come out with, given a decent sized dictionary. Here, in other words, is
some sample output....

Remember: All these sentences are generated entirely by the computer, using
words from a dictionary. There is a small dictionary to begin with, which
will expand automatically with any new words entered by the user.


         The boys will have a powerful computer.

         Can you photograph a giraffe?

         Do you know their language?

         Are they going to make a cake?

         The dog chased the cat.

         Did the cat eat many fish?

         He is going to be the king.

         You are going to learn an easy language.


... and so on.


            @{"    Overview    " link overview}

            @{"Back to begining" link main}

@endnode

@node Install "Installation"

Installation
~~~~~~~~~~~~
Well, I haven't written an install script, I'm afraid.

But there's not much to it, though, so you shouldn't need to worry.

The archive should extract into a single directory, which should run from
wherever you decide to copy it to.

So just copy the directory anywhere, and you're nearly all set.

The only other thing to do is copy the Amos.library to the libs: directory
if you don't already have it there.


That's it. Now go enjoy the program, and stop messing round with boring
stuff like this......

            @{"Back to begining" link main}

@endnode

@node Parser "Command Set"

Program Command Parser:
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
In addition to interpreting sentences, the program also has a small command
set. These are used by entering either a hash (#) or a star (*) as the first
letter of your input, followed immediately by the command. The commands at
the moment are:
   #quit
   #speak
   #help
   #repeat
   #load
   #save
   #correct
   #dir
   #cls
   #autosave
   #check
   #print
   #version
   #show     <--- New v1.21
   #topic    <--- New v1.23
   #question <--- New v1.30
   #log      <--- New v1.33
   #palette  <--- New v1.42

· #quit:     Quits HAL 9001 back to AmigaDos.
· #speak:    Requires the Amiga's speech synth from AmigaDos 1.x (works with
             AmigaDos 2.x and 3.x, but wasn't supplied with the later vers)
· #help:     Brings up a page of info about the program. Not really very
             helpful - you're better off reading this file!
· #repeat:   Repeats last sentence.
· #load:     Reloads the dictionary. Unless you make a mess of the
             dictionary in memory, you shouldn't need this command.
· #save:     Saves the dictionary.
· #correct:  Allows a limited amount of error correction. Only of any real
             use for spelling mastikes.
· #dir:      Allows you to change the directory on disk to load/save the
             dictionary to/from.
· #cls:      Simply clears the screen.
· #autosave: Will save the dictionary whenever it changes. In practice this
             means just about every time you enter anything.
· #check:    Forces the computer to check if the dictionary has been saved
             when you #quit out of the program.
· #print:    Will print all the computer's replies onto the printer as well
             as the screen.
· #version:  Brings up the version number for reference.
· #show:     On it's own, it brings up a list of all the words the computer
             knows (or at least, all the nouns, verbs, adjectives and
             adverbs). Or, you can type a word to look up, and it will give
             you more details on that word.
· #topic:    Makes the program seem more inteligent, by forcing it's
             sentences to stick to a topic. If you enter a sentence, HAL
             will try to make it's next sentence use at least one of the
             words in your sentence. It's not guaranteed to work every time,
             but with luck, it should seem more conversational, rather than
             simply outputting random sentences.
· #question: HAL now has the ability to ask you questions. It still won't
             understand your answers, though!  If you prefer to just stick
             with it saying normal statement-type sentences, set this flag to
             OFF (it defaults to ON).
             Also, though: This option allows you as well as ON and OFF, to
             specify a number as the parameter - the higher, the more likely
             it is to ask you a question.
             eg: 0=Off; 1=50%; 3=75%, 9=90%. Set it to whatever suits you.
· #log:      Toggles the conversation logging. Uses a parameter of ON or OFF.
             Anything else as the parameter is treated as a filename for the
             log file. The log file is a file that stores the conversation
             you have with HAL. Each sentence you input, and each that HAL
             outputs, will be written to the log file, as well as a few info
             lines, when certain events happen. Each line on the log file is
             marked with "User:", "HAL:" or "Info:".
             For more info, see the @{"log file" link log} section of this
             guide.
· #palette:  Cosmetics. This allows you to change the colours used by HAL.
             This is in response to a user request - someone didn't like
             the default colours! (disaster, eh?)
             Anyway, there's two ways to use this: You can either pick one
             of the pre-defined colour sets, or build up your own.
             To pick a pre-defined set, use the set number as a parameter:
             eg:  @{b}#PALETTE SET1@{ub}    or just   @{b}#PALETTE 1@{ub}
             There are currently six pre-defined sets to chose from. Set one
             is a the default. (Slightly modified since the last version)
             Using #PALETTE on it's own (without params) will reset you to
             the default (ie set 1).
             Alternatively, you can build your palette colour-by-colour. The
             syntax is #PALETTE <colour num>:<red>:<green>:<blue>
             eg:  @{b}#PALETTE 0:15:15:15@{ub}   will change your background to white.
             You'll need to call it for each colour you want to change if
             you use this syntax.
             The range for the colour numbers is 0-15. 15:15:15 is white,
             and 0:0:0 is black.
             My recommendation is to first pick a set that's close to what
             you want, and change it from there.
             The colours used:
                 0=Background;      1=HAL's sentences;  2=User input;
                 3=Flashing cursor; 4=Command output;   5,6,7=unused


I should mention that the speech synthesis is very effecive! If you have a
newer Amiga, you should try to get hold of the neccessary libraries. It is
totally different from just having the Amiga simply repeat anything you give
it to say - it almost seems to have come alive when it starts saying it's
one sentences!

The #repeat command is only of any real use with the speech. You might get a
particularly weird sentence that you want it to say again (once you've
gathered all the family round the computer!).

The #speak, #autosave, #check #print #topic and #question commands have an
optional parameter. If you enter ON or OFF after the command, it will force
the appropriate setting. If you do not enter the parameter, the commands
will toggle the setting.

The #show command is very useful for checking the correctness of your
dictionary before trying #correct. type #show <verb>, and you'll see all the
verb's conjugations, as the computer sees them. I plan to also show the word
links in this section too.

#correct has been partly disabled in this version, because it's not fully
operational. If you really really want to use it, type "#correct force", but
you should know that the computer will correct verbs automatically if you
enter a sentence that proves that it's existing conjugations are incorrect,
which probably makes the #correct feature more trouble than it's worth.

#check and #question default to ON; #speak, #autosave, #print and #log all
default to OFF.

As of version 1.34, you can use the tooltypes to set these to your preferred
settings. See the @{"preferences" link ttypes} section for more details.


            @{"Back to begining" link Main}
@endnode

@node ttypes "Preferences / Tool-types"

Setting the default prefs
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
HAL has quite a number of options now, most of which can be switched on or
off at runtime using #command (see the @{"parser" link Parser} chapter).

Now, new in version 1.34 (Sept 98), it can use tooltypes to set the initial
defaults of most of the options.
So all those users who were getting cross because you had to re-set all your
preferred settings, this is the chapter for you.

To use them, go into HAL's icon info from Workbench, and simply add the
tooltypes for your chosen options.

If no tooltype appears for an option, the existing default is used.
The tooltypes can be standalone (ie just the command word), or given a value.
If the value is "OFF" or "0" (ie zero), the option is switched off. Otherwise
it is switched on by it's presence in the tooltypes list.

The options available for tooltypes are (in no special order):

  SPEAK     TOPIC     AUTOSAVE
  PRINT     LOG       CHECK
  QUESTION  PALETTE
  
These operate on an on/off basis, in the same way as their counterpart
commands within the program. (again, see the @{"parser" link Parser} chapter)
 Examples: @{b}SPEAK=ON@{ub}
           @{b}TOPIC=OFF@{ub}

The exception is the PALETTE option.
This operates in the same way as the #PALETTE command in the parser.
 Examples: @{b}PALETTE=SET4@{ub}
           @{b}PALETTE=0:15:15:15@{ub}


Some of you who know Amos Pro will be asking now 'How did he get Amos to read
the tooltypes??'
The answer is that I used an Amos extension called AMCAF.
Amcaf is a shareware (I have registered) extension to Amos Pro, which gives
a large number of very useful commands, including accessing the tooltypes,
support for a second mouse (great for two player games!), and loads more.
If you use Amos, you really do need this extension!


            @{"Back to begining" link Main}

@endnode

@node log

The Log File
~~~~~~~~~~~~

The log file is a new feature (v1.33) in HAL, which allows you to record
your conversations with HAL on file.

I've given it an entire chapter of this guide, because I feel that it's
quite an important feature.

The feature is controlled by the @{"#log" link parser} command.

At it's simplest level, this is a simple @{b}#log on@{ub} to turn on logging,
and @{b}#log off@{ub} to turn it off again, or simple @{b}#log@{ub} on it's
own to toggle the setting.
You can also give it a filename as the parameter instead of On or Off, which
allows you to specify the name of file that will be created for the log.
If you don't specify a filename, the program will default to @{i}Nicolas.Log@{ui},
unless you already set up logging before, in which case the previous file
name will be used.

Note that creating the log file overwrites any existing file that may have
that name, so you should be careful what name you chose.

The log file is good for keeping a record of your conversations with HAL.
I'm not sure quite what you'd do with it once you've kept it, but I imagine
that also applies to the #print command, which has been there since the
begining.

In fact, I will say that the log could be very useful for debugging purposes.
If you spot a bug in HAL, and you have a log file that shows it, sending the
log file to me may well speed up the fix.

            @{"Back to begining" link Main}

@endnode

@node Bugs

Bugs!!!
~~~~~~~

(What.... in @{i}my@{ui} software!!??!?)

Well, ok. There are a few I know of, and in a program of this sort, there
are bound to be plenty I don't know about, too.

   · The program seems to sometimes find blank nouns, which make some of
     it's sentences sound a bit wrong. Hopefully I'll find the problem
     for the next version.
     (1.30: I haven't seen any for a while... let me know if this is still
     a problem)

   · Since it's written in Amos, all known problems with Amos apply to this
     program (and that's quite a lot of bugs, believe me!). Not much I can
     do about that, short of a complete re-write in another language...  :-(
     (And no, I don't have the time to do that!)

   · The #correct command doesn't work, so don't even try it.
     (well, you can try it, but it'll mess up your data....)

   · The program simply isn't clever enough to work out a verb's entire
     conjugations, but it does try to guess sometimes to avoid asking you too
     many questions. If it guesses wrong, you'll get some strange sounding
     sentences, but the dictionary can be repaired by entering the computer's
     wrong sentence correctly, and answering the questions as normal.
     That's not really a bug..

   · Although I've added the ability to the program's sentence-builder to
     generate questions as well as statements, I haven't made any changes
     to the input parser, so you will probably make some problems in the
     dictionary if you start entering questions. Stick to statements for
     the time being.
     (that said, the parser will have a bash at interpreting whatever you
     throw at it, so if you feel brave, you could give it a try)
     And of course, it certainly won't make any attempt to answer you if
     you type in a question.... although with #topic turned on, it might
     just fluke it.


That's about it.... although obviously there'll be more and worse that I've
yet to discover. If you find anything, please let me know (see my @{"address" link address}).


@endnode

@node Technical "Technical Details"

How it works:
~~~~~~~~~~~~~
(A chapter to be skipped by the faint hearted)

Actally, it isn't really all that difficult in theory, although you'd
probably have several mental breakdowns if you tried to read through the
source code without knowing what was going on!

The basic principle is to link words together.
As you will probably already have noticed, the basic sentence structure goes
along the lines of "The <noun1> <verb>s the <noun2>". Or something similar.
When you enter a sentence like this, the computer looks for the words in
it's dictionary. When it has either found them all or got you to tell it
about the words, it links the words. This sentence would only need two
links: Noun1 -> Noun2, and Noun2 -> Verb. If your sentence contains any
adverbs or adjectives, these will be linked to the appropriate noun or verb.

Let me explain these links.
Noun2 -> Verb lets the computer know what can be done to the noun. For
example, meat can be eaten; castles can be attacked; etc.
Noun1 -> Noun2 lets the computer know what can do these things to the noun.
To continue the above examples, a cat can eat the meat; a knight can attack
the castle.

The computer now knows what can be done to what, and by what. Anything that
can be done to noun2 can, as far as the computer is concerned, be done to it
by noun1. This might make some the computer produce some interesting
sentences if the above is not true. For example, you might have earlier
input a sentence about someone cooking some meat, which will now result in
the computer being quite happy to tell you that the cat is cooking some
meat!
Ah well. AI? Not a chance in my lifetime, matey!

The biggest limitation to this approach is speed. Most of the time, you'll
get pretty quick responses, but sometimes, especially on slower Amigas, it
will take quite a while to think up a sentence (anything more than a few
seconds is slow, although I have had to wait over a minute on one occasion).
This happens when it picks words that do not have links to make a sentence.
In this case, it will try with it's existing choices three times to make a
sentence before giving up and starting from scratch.
To avoid this as much as possible, give each word you enter as many links as
possible and in the case of nouns, it is good to give them links as both the
primary noun or the secondary noun, so that wherever the computer picks them
to go, they will have the correct links.

Now that I've added questions to it's abilities, that's a whole new arena.
It's not really much of a change though. All the above still applies, it
just has to re-arrange some of the words, and maybe add one or two new ones.
Nothing special.. randomly decide if it's going to be a question before we
start, and make sure everything is arranged in the appropriate order,
depending on the result of that.

The program is only good for speaking English. The sentence structures it
understands are typically English, and the built in words like the pronouns
and so on are all English. It @{i}could@{ui} be modified to speak another
language, but I am not going to do this unless I get @{b}*lots*@{ub} of requests.
(and a few lessons in whatever language... <grin>)

Since I'm programming it in Amos rather than C, I have had to place a limit
on the maximum number of words possible. At the moment, you can only have up
to one hundred of each nouns, verbs, adjectives and adverbs, and words
entered as 'others'. In practive, I have yet to come anywhere near that
limit, but if anyone wants a bigger dictionary, and you think you have the
memory to handle it, let me know, and I'll arrange it. (it's not a big deal)

That is a basic run-down of how it works. Not exactly the easiest thing in
the world to understand, but then if it was, we'd all be writing these
programs.  :-)

               @{"Back to begining" link Main}
@endnode

@node DistNote "Notes to distributors"
Notes to distributors
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Thank you for distributing HAL9001. The following are some guidelines and
rules for distributors of this product, broken down into different methods
of distribution.

Floppy disk
~~~~~~~~~~~
This applies to most, if not all the PD companies who advertise in the
various magazines, and most Amiga user groups.
The program may not be sold on a floppy disk for more than Ł2.00 (UK) or
$3.00 (US), regardless of what else is on the disk. The disk must not be
less than 80% full if you plan to charge any money for it.

CD-ROMs
~~~~~~~
There are now numerous PD CD-ROMs available for the Amiga. If this program
appears on a CD, the disc's contents must be predominantly freely
distributable, and the disc should cost roughly the same as the Aminet
CD-ROMs.  Aminet has explicit permission to use it.

On line
~~~~~~~
On line services may freely archive the program and docs, provided the
entire distribution is included in the archive. A small description of the
program could be kept separate from the archive to allow subscribers to see
what it is without having to download.
(eg like the Aminet .readme)

Magazine Coverdisks
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Many magazines are sold with disks taped to the front. This program may be
included on one of these disks. I expect to be informed, although I'm not
asking for anything else (it'd be nice, tho'!  ;-).

(thanks to Amiga Plus Magazin of Germany for asking permission to put it
on their cover CD)

(Amiga Format 'forgot' to tell me when they put it on their subscribers
superdisk. hmmm.... ah well, I forgive you :-) .. after all, it was on the
subs disk of the first issue of my subscription... spooky, huh?)

To all distributors
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
I would appreciate being told if you are distributing the program. It makes
it easier for me to keep everyone informed about updates.


