@node Author

About ME:
~~~~~~~~~
It's a well known fact that most people like to talk about themselves, and
programmers are no exception to the rule. This programmer is very much in
line with the rule, so here's my chance to be incredibly modest - Not.

I grew up in England.  In 1991 my family moved to South Africa (this was
not long after Mandela was freed), and I finished my schooling there. I
studied programming a little bit in Pretoria, and got my first job as a
programmer, writing in-house PC applications for a manufacturing firm.

In 1996, I left South Africa, and returned to England, where I now work
for a software house, as part of the development team for a large system
that is sold to the hiring industry.

Apart from Amos Pro (which I use because I've got so many unfinished Amos
projects it'll take forever to clear them down), I can program a variety of
languages. I studied C and Pascal, and my jobs have had me programming in
Clarion and Dibol - both lesser known languages, but both quite pleasant to
work with - as well as Cobol (which I hate). I've also spent time learning
a any other languages I can get my hands on.

On my desk, there used to be two Amigas A4000s. I've sold one of them now,
as I didn't use it much any more. The other has a Cyberstorm 060, 1.2 gig
SCSI Hdisk, CD-Rom, 18 megs of Ram, and a Picasso IV card.
(I loooove my Amiga!)

My main interest in programming is for the challenge - that's why I wrote
this.
Other projects I've got close to completing include a text adventure game
(with another one on the way), a couple of puzzle-em-up games (which I won't
release until I can draw some better graphics), and so on.
Take a look at my web page for more (http://village.vossnet.co.uk/c/champion),
or on Aminet.


            @{"WhateverYouLike-Ware" link WYLW}

            @{"  Back to begining  " link Main}
@endnode

